  "prompt": "Why wasn't Lord Krishna married to Radha?",
  "response": "According to Hindu mythology and various religious texts, Lord Krishna and Radha were not married due to several spiritual and philosophical reasons:\n\n1. Divine Love: Their relationship is considered a pure, spiritual, and platonic form of love (bhakti) that transcends physical marriage.\n\n2. Symbolic Representation: Their love is seen as a metaphorical representation of the soul's devotion to the divine, rather than a conventional romantic relationship.\n\n3. Social Constraints: Radha was already married to another man, and Krishna was a prince with multiple responsibilities.\n\n4. Spiritual Significance: Their relationship symbolizes the ultimate connection between the devotee (Radha) and the divine (Krishna).\n\n5. Mythological Context: In most traditional narratives, Radha is portrayed as Krishna's beloved consort, but not his legal wife.\n\n6. Spiritual Interpretation: Their love is considered a divine, spiritual bond that goes beyond societal norms of marriage.\n\n7. Philosophical Meaning: Their relationship represents the eternal, unconditional love between the individual soul and the supreme consciousness.\n\nWhile they were not married in the traditional sense, Radha is still considered Krishna's eternal consort in Hindu theology, representing the highest form of spiritual love and devotion.",
